The President of the United States, Barack Obama, and Prime Minister David Cameron of the United Kingdom discussed their concerns about the situation in eastern Ukraine. They praised the Ukrainian government for its constructive proposals in the Geneva discussions, which aim to expand local governance and protect the rights of all Ukrainians. Both leaders emphasized the need for Russia to take immediate actions to de-escalate the situation, including influencing the irregular forces in eastern Ukraine to lay down their arms and vacate the seized buildings. The President and the Prime Minister stated that the United States and Europe are ready to impose further measures on Russia if de-escalation does not occur promptly.